  "prompt": "What is a boy/girl called when he/she is 1-6 years old, 6-11years old, 11-14 years old, and 14-18 years old?",
  "response": "Here\u2019s a breakdown of the terms commonly used to describe boys and girls at different ages:\n\n1. **1\u20136 years old**:  \n   - **Toddler** (1\u20133 years): After infancy, a child who is just learning to walk and explore.  \n   - **Preschooler** (3\u20136 years): A child who is not yet in formal schooling or is in preschool/kindergarten.  \n   - General term: **Young child** or **Little boy/girl**.\n\n2. **6\u201311 years old**:  \n   - **Child**: This is the general term for this age group.  \n   - **School-age child**: Refers to kids in elementary school.  \n   - **Tween** (9\u201312 years): Sometimes used for kids who are nearing adolescence but are not yet teens.\n\n3. **11\u201314 years old**:  \n   - **Preteen** or **Tween**: Often used for kids who are approaching their teenage years but are not yet 13.  \n   - **Early adolescent**: In developmental terms, this is the beginning of adolescence.\n\n4. **14\u201318 years old**:  \n   - **Teenager** or **Teen**: The most common term for this age group.  \n   - **Adolescent**: Refers to this developmental stage, which spans from around 12\u201318 years old.  \n   - **Late adolescent**: Specifically for those closer to 18, transitioning to adulthood.\n\nThese terms may vary slightly depending on cultural or regional contexts, but they are widely used in developmental psychology and everyday language.",
